{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524451"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:04:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:04:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13995"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13995"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.06,0.09,0.28,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6629"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51578"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6629"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13995"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36883"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2639"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13462"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34907"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51578"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of a moderately pruritic rash on his trunk. The rash developed one week after he was discharged from hospital following a cardioplasty for severe achalasia. He has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His medications include aspirin, atorvastatin, and nifedipine. He denies any new medications or changes to his home environment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The rash consists of multiple erythematous, edematous papules in clusters on his trunk only. Some lesions show signs of excoriation. There are no vesicles, bullae, or scaling present.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral acyclovir","Oral fluconazole","Oral prednisolone","Topical permethrin","Topical betamethasone dipropionate"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with \u003Cstrong\u003Epapular urticaria\u003C/strong\u003E, a hypersensitivity reaction that typically manifests as pruritic papules in cluster. The condition can occur without a clear trigger, as in this case, but is often associated with hypersensitivity to insect bites such as fleas, mites, bed bugs, mosquitoes or environmental allergens.  The papules or blisters are itchy and may last from weeks to months without treatment.  Whilst more common in children under 10 years of age, it can occur in adults and it is not contagious.  Skin biopsy can confirm the diagnosis.  Treatment can include avoiding the cause if known: pets outside, changing mattress or wearing protective clothing. Papular uriticaria self-resolves once desensitisation has occurred to the cause however this may take years and can reoccur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical betamethasone dipropionate\u003C/strong\u003E (a potent topical corticosteroid) is the most appropriate initial management for this patient. Topical corticosteroids are the first-line treatment for papular urticaria, as they effectively reduce inflammation and pruritus. They should be applied sparingly to affected areas, typically once or twice daily for a short course (1-2 weeks).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E (a systemic corticosteroid) would be considered for more severe or widespread cases of papular urticaria that do not respond to topical treatments. However, it is not the first-line treatment due to potential systemic side effects, especially in an older patient like this and for the rash only on his trunk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral acyclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral medication used primarily for herpes simplex virus infections. It is not indicated for papular urticaria, which is not caused by a viral infection.  Herpes simplex virus show a vesicular rash which is not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical permethrin\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat scabies and other ectoparasitic infections. While papular urticaria can sometimes be confused with scabies, it is often severely itchy and burrows may be seen for the scabies mite.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral fluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E is an antifungal medication used for various fungal infections, not a hypersensitivity reaction.  Fungal infections tend to be scaley or ring-shaped and red rather than papules as in this image. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to topical corticosteroids, management of papular urticaria often includes oral antihistamines to control pruritus, and patient education about avoiding potential triggers. If symptoms persist or worsen despite initial treatment, referral to a dermatologist may be warranted for further evaluation and management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Papular urticaria can occur without a clear trigger, but is often associated with hypersensitivity to insect bites or environmental allergens.","Treatment for papular urticaria usually involves topical corticosteroids and oral antihistamines, with systemic corticosteroids reserved for severe cases."],"references":["Lim D, Jibreal H.  Papular Urticaria. The Australasian College of Dermatologists. 2019. Available in: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/atoz/papular-urticaria/","Oakley A, Koch K.  Papular Uritcaria. In: Dermnet NZ. 2021. Available in: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/papular-urticaria"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36883"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13995"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20889"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20889"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xCYvfwA2rtDjrlzwerUPCoxkRF30Qs.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xCYvfwA2rtDjrlzwerUPCoxkRF30Qs.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36883"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-26T21:22:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-26T21:23:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6629"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51578"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","lin